>[Question]
>What is meant by the x-intercept of a quadratic function and the y-
>intercept of a quadratic function?
>
>[Difficulty]
>Well, I don't really understand the two questions. 
>
>[Thoughts]
>I thought the meaning of the x-intercept of the quadratic function 
>is where the solutions of a quadratic equation is but I'm having 
>second thoughts. I don't really know about the y-intercept of the 
>quadratic equation.

Hello G. B.,

The x-intercepts are the values of x for which the graph intersectes the x-axis; so they are 
the solutions of the quadratic equation.  The y-intercepts are where the graph crosses the 
y-axis, that is, let x=0 in the equation.

- Doctor Jerry, The Math Forum
  <http://mathforum.org/dr.math/>
